Read thisfirst:\nArchitectural innovations\nTransformers and large language/vision models\n\nOriginal transformer. The transformer architecture introduced in 2017 replaced recurrence with selfattention. It applies multihead selfattention in encoder and decoder blocks, allowing the model to capture longrange dependencies efficiently. Vision Transformers (ViT) adapt this architecture to images by treating an image as a sequence of patches; they typically require large datasets and careful regularization but match or exceed CNNs when properly scaled\narxiv.org\n. Recent improvements combine convolution and selfattention to capture local and global features. For example, the MaxViT architecture stacks convolutional layers with local and global attention blocks to improve scalability on images\narxiv.org\n.\n\nGraph Transformers. Graph transformers (GTs) extend the transformers attention mechanism to nonEuclidean data such as molecular graphs or networked data. A recent survey categorizes GT architectures into four strategies\narxiv.org\n:\n\nMultilevel graph tokenization edges, subgraphs or multihop neighborhoods are encoded as tokens so that attention can learn topological relationships.\n\nStructural positional encoding structural information (e.g., node degrees, shortest paths) is injected into positional encodings to reflect graph topology.\n\nStructureaware attention the attention matrix is modified using graphderived structural information so that attention scores respect the connectivity of the graph.\n\nModel ensembles messagepassing GNNs are combined with transformers to encode local structure while transformers provide global context.\n\nGraph transformers have been applied to molecules, proteins, traffic networks and astrodata. They overcome GNN problems such as oversmoothing and oversquashing by capturing longrange dependencies\narxiv.org\n.\n\nDiffusion models. Denoising diffusion probabilistic models (DDPMs) are generative models that learn to transform Gaussian noise into realistic samples via a learned denoising process. A recent survey on efficient diffusion models divides efficiency techniques into three categories\nopenreview.net\n:\n\nAlgorithmlevel methods (e.g., better noise schedules, fast sampling, model compression) that reduce the number of denoising steps.\n\nSystemlevel methods (hardwaresoftware codesign, parallel computing, caching) to accelerate training/inference.\n\nSpecialized frameworks that integrate mixedprecision, distributed training and optimized kernels for diffusion models.\n\nStateoftheart diffusion models such as Stable Diffusion XL and DALLE3 dominate image and video generation. They outperform GANs on realism as measured by Frchet Inception Distance (FID)\ntechtarget.com\n and can be finetuned for domainspecific generation (e.g., simulating astrophysical images).\n\nGenerative adversarial networks (GANs). GANs use a generatordiscriminator adversarial game to produce realistic outputs. Architectural advances include StyleGAN for highquality images and CycleGAN for domain translation. However, diffusion models and transformers have largely supplanted GANs in 2025 due to stability and fidelity issues.\n\nGraph neural networks (GNNs). GNNs perform message passing on graph structures; variants include Graph Convolutional Networks, Graph Attention Networks (GATs), Graph Isomorphism Networks (GIN), and spectral methods. Oversmoothing and limited receptive fields motivate the use of graph transformers\narxiv.org\n.\n\nSpiking neural networks (SNNs). SNNs use binary spikes and eventdriven computation to achieve energy efficiency. A 2024 review notes that SNNs offer high biological plausibility and lowpower accumulation compared with traditional neural nets\npmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\n. There are two main training routes:\n\nANNtoSNN conversion converting pretrained artificial neural networks by replacing ReLU with spiking neurons and scaling weights\npmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\n. This suffers from long simulation times and limited flexibility.\n\nDirect training with surrogate gradients unfolding the SNN over time and using backpropagation through time with surrogate gradients\npmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\n. This approach handles temporal data and allows novel architectures (e.g., transformerbased SNNs)\npmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\n.\n\nRecent work has produced transformerbased SNNs that approach CNN/transformer performance on ImageNet while using far fewer spikes\npmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\n. Spiking models are attractive for astrobiology instruments that require realtime, lowpower inference.\n\nHybrid and domainspecific architectures\n\nVisionTransformer hybrids combine CNNs for local feature extraction and transformers for global context. Examples include Conformer and Swin Transformer. These models achieve high accuracy on ImageNet by merging convolution and selfattention\narxiv.org\n.\n\nTemporal Transformers integrate spectral methods or statespace models to capture longrange timeseries dependencies (e.g., S4, Mamba). They can be applied to irregularly sampled astrobiology timeseries such as light curves.\n\nGraphdiffusion hybrids use diffusion models on graphs (e.g., graph diffusion transformers) to generate graphs or to augment graph training data.\n\nTraining paradigms\nParadigm\tKey idea / mechanism\tTypical use cases\tNotes\nSupervised learning\tModel learns from labeled data; loss measures discrepancy between predictions and ground truth.\tClassification/regression tasks such as galaxy morphology or exoplanet classification.\tRequires labeled datasets, which can be expensive in astrobiology.\nSelfsupervised/contrastive learning\tThe model learns invariances by contrasting positive pairs (similar samples) against negative pairs (dissimilar samples). Contrastive learning pushes embeddings of similar inputs closer while separating dissimilar ones\nv7labs.com\n.\tPretraining on unlabeled astrophysical images, timeseries or spectra; representation learning for downstream tasks.\tPositive samples may be different augmentations of the same spectrum, while negatives are different objects.\nMetalearning\tLearn to learn: train a metalearner across many tasks so it can quickly adapt to new tasks. Three common approaches metricbased, modelbased and optimizationbased differ in how they generalize\nlilianweng.github.io\n.\tFewshot classification of rare astrophysical events, transfer from simulated to real data.\tMetricbased methods (e.g., prototypical networks) compute distances in embedding space; modelbased approaches use RNNs or memory modules; optimizationbased approaches learn initial weights that adapt quickly (e.g., MAML).\nCurriculum learning\tTrain the model from easy examples to harder ones, mimicking human curricula\nmn.cs.tsinghua.edu.cn\n.\tTraining models on astrophysical spectra starting from high signaltonoise samples and gradually including noisier or rarer spectra.\tRequires a difficulty measurer and learning scheduler to order training samples\nmn.cs.tsinghua.edu.cn\n. Variants include selfpaced learning and teacherstudent curricula.\nReinforcement learning (RL)\tAgents learn actions that maximize cumulative rewards.\tPlanning optimal observation schedules, controlling autonomous exploration vehicles, or adaptive optics control.\tDeep RL algorithms (e.g., PPO, SAC) can benefit from curriculum learning and metalearning for sample efficiency.\nContinual/online learning\tModels incrementally learn from nonstationary data streams without catastrophic forgetting.\tMonitoring variable stars, solar flare prediction, or longterm spectrophotometric monitoring.\tTechniques include rehearsal buffers, regularization, and memorybased architectures.\nUnsupervised / generative learning\tModels learn data distribution without labels (e.g., autoencoders, VAEs, GANs, diffusion models).\tGenerating synthetic astrophysical images or spectra, denoising observations, data augmentation.\tDiffusion models currently provide stateoftheart generative performance and can be finetuned on astrophysics data.\nOptimization techniques and best practices\n\nAdaptive learningrate schedulers. Schedulers such as cosine annealing, onecycle, and exponential decay adjust the learning rate during training to improve convergence. The cyclical onecycle schedule often yields faster convergence and better generalization in transformer training. Gradient clipping prevents exploding gradients by clipping the gradient to a maximum threshold during backpropagation\nneptune.ai\n. There are two variants: clipping by value (cap gradients within \nneptune.ai\n) and clipping by norm (rescale gradients to a fixed norm\nneptune.ai\n). Both stabilize training and are standard in recurrent networks and transformers.\n\nMixedprecision training. Using halfprecision (float16/bfloat16) instead of full 32bit floats reduces memory and increases throughput. The PyTorch amp API simplifies mixedprecision by automatically casting operations and scaling loss. Mixedprecision training can accelerate matrix multiplications and convolutions by up to 16 on modern GPUs\npytorch.org\n and reduces memory usage, enabling larger batch sizes or models. Mixed precision is essential for training large models like GPT3\npytorch.org\n.\n\nOptimizer choices. AdamW is widely used for transformers because it decouples weight decay from gradient updates. RMSProp and Adagrad are common in SNNs. For diffusion models, optimizers with momentum and adaptive learning rate (Adam, AdaFactor) are standard.\n\nRegularization. Techniques such as dropout, layer normalization, label smoothing and data augmentation remain critical. In graph transformers, structural regularizers (e.g., edge dropout) mitigate overfitting.\n\nInitialization and normalization. Proper initialization (e.g., Xavier, Kaiming) and normalization (layer norm, batch norm) are crucial for stabilizing deep networks. Graph transformers often incorporate nodewise normalization and residual connections.\n\nDistributed and memoryefficient training. Model parallelism, tensor parallelism and pipeline parallelism are required for training trillionparameter models. Activation checkpointing and gradient accumulation reduce memory usage. For diffusion models, systemlevel optimizations and hardwaresoftware codesign improve throughput\nopenreview.net\n.\n\nEvaluation protocols and benchmarks\n\nClassification tasks. Accuracy and topk accuracy (e.g., ImageNet top1/top5) remain standard. For imbalanced or multilabel tasks, F1score and area under the ROC curve (AUC) provide better insight. In graph tasks, ranking metrics such as mean reciprocal rank (MRR) and normalized mutual information (NMI) are used.\n\nGenerative models. The Frchet Inception Distance (FID) measures realism and diversity of generated images by comparing the statistics of generated and real images in the Inceptionv3 feature space. A lower FID indicates closer match to real data\ntechtarget.com\n. The Inception Score (IS) and CLIPscore are also used but are less robust.\n\nNaturallanguage tasks. BLEU and ROUGE scores evaluate translation and summarization quality; perplexity evaluates language models. In largelanguage models, multitask benchmarks such as MMLU, BIGBench, and ASTROQA evaluate reasoning and domain adaptation.\n\nTimeseries and spectral data. Metrics include mean absolute error (MAE), root mean square error (RMSE), dynamic time warping distance (DTW), and detection rates for events (precision/recall). For exoplanet transit detection, the false positive rate is critical.\n\nAstrobiology benchmarks. No universal benchmark exists, but relevant datasets include:\n\nGalaxy10 and Galaxy Zoo for galaxy morphologies.\n\nTESS and Kepler lightcurves for exoplanet detection.\n\nSloan Digital Sky Survey (SDSS) spectra for spectroscopic classification.\n\nLSST simulated timeseries for variable star classification.\n\nComparisons should control for compute budget, parameter count and training data. Graph transformers and diffusion models are computeheavy; spiking models offer energy efficiency but currently lag in accuracy on large benchmarks\npmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\n.\n\nSample leaderboard (as of August2025)\nModel / architecture\tDomain\tParams\tDataset / task\tPerformance\nGPT4o\tLanguage / multimodal\t~1T\tMultitask (MMLU, GSM8K)\tStateoftheart reasoning and generative performance.\nVisionTransformer (ViTG/14)\tImage classification\t2G+\tImageNet\t~90% top1 accuracy; competitive with CNNs.\nStable DiffusionXL\tImage generation\t2.3G\tLAION & custom datasets\tFID <7 on general images.\nGraphTransformerLarge (GTL)\tGraph tasks (molecules)\t300M\tOGBLSC PCQM4M\tCompetitive with messagepassing GNNs (MAE <0.1 eV).\nSNNTransformer2024\tVision (eventcamera)\t200M\tDVSCIFAR10\t94% accuracy\npmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov\n while using <0.3 spikes per neuron.\n\nNote: Parameter counts and metrics vary across publications. The leaderboard emphasizes the tradeoff between model size, accuracy and energy efficiency. Models are ranked qualitatively by scalability and relevance to astrobiology.\n\nCode and training pipelines\nTypical PyTorch pipeline for image classification\nimport torch\nimport torch.nn as nn\nfrom torchvision import datasets, transforms\nfrom torch.optim import AdamW\nfrom torch.optim.lr_scheduler import CosineAnnealingLR\n\n# Data loading\ntransform = transforms.Compose([\n transforms.Resize(224),\n transforms.CenterCrop(224),\n transforms.ToTensor(),\n transforms.Normalize(mean=[0.485,0.456,0.406], std=[0.229,0.224,0.225]),\n])\ntrain_ds = datasets.ImageFolder('/data/train', transform=transform)\ntrain_loader = torch.utils.data.DataLoader(train_ds, batch_size=32, shuffle=True)\n\n# Model (Vision Transformer)\nmodel = timm.create_model('vit_base_patch16_224', pretrained=False, num_classes=10)\n\n# Optimizer and scheduler\noptimizer = AdamW(model.parameters(), lr=1e-3, weight_decay=1e-2)\nscheduler = CosineAnnealingLR(optimizer, T_max=100)\n\ncriterion = nn.CrossEntropyLoss()\n\nfor epoch in range(100):\n model.train()\n for images, labels in train_loader:\n optimizer.zero_grad()\n outputs = model(images)\n loss = criterion(outputs, labels)\n loss.backward()\n torch.nn.utils.clip_grad_norm_(model.parameters(), max_norm=1.0) # gradient clipping\n optimizer.step()\n scheduler.step()\n\n\nThis pipeline applies data normalization, uses AdamW with weight decay, cosine annealing, and gradient clipping to stabilize training. Mixed precision can be added using torch.amp.autocast and GradScaler. Similar pipelines exist in TensorFlow and JAX.\n\nTypical diffusion model training loop\n# Pseudocode for DDPM training\ndef train_step(x0):\n # sample time step\nt = torch.randint(1, T, (batch_size,))\n # sample noise\nnoise = torch.randn_like(x0)\n # forward diffuse x0 to xt\nxt = q_sample(x0, t, noise)\n # predict noise using UNet\npred_noise = model(xt, t)\n # compute loss (e.g., simple L2 between predicted and true noise)\nloss = F.mse_loss(pred_noise, noise)\n loss.backward()\n optimizer.step()\n\n\nEfficient training uses fewer denoising steps (e.g., deterministic diffusion), memoryefficient attention blocks, and mixedprecision. Finetuning on domainspecific data often requires only a few thousand steps.\n\nSpiking neural network training pipeline (surrogate gradient)\n# Pseudocode for direct training with surrogate gradients\nfor epoch in range(num_epochs):\n for batch in dataloader:\n spike_inputs = encode_to_spikes(batch['input']) # encode data into spike trains\n membrane_potential = 0\n spikes = []\n for t in range(T):\n membrane_potential = update_neuron(membrane_potential, spike_inputs[:, t])\n spike_output = (membrane_potential >= threshold).float()\n spikes.append(spike_output)\n # compute loss using output spikes vs. target\n loss = criterion(torch.stack(spikes, dim=1), batch['target'])\n # surrogate gradient backpropagation\n loss.backward()\n optimizer.step()\n\n\nSurrogate gradients approximate the derivative of the nondifferentiable spike function with a smooth function (e.g., sigmoid). Frameworks such as SpyTorch and Norse provide modules for spiking neurons. Mixedprecision is less common due to binary spikes.\n\nIntegration guidelines for astrobiology data\nSpectroscopic data\n\nPreprocessing: Normalize spectra, correct for redshift, and handle missing wavelengths. n_state":"unseen"}],"feedbackStates":{},"toolUseStates":{},"draftExchange":{"request_message":"SYSTEM / ROLE\r\nYou are Augment Code, acting as a principal ML/Systems engineer and code auditor. If a spec is ambiguous, resolve it by reading the code and tests, inferring intent, and implementing a concrete, production-grade solution. Keep iterating until every check passes.\r\n\r\nCONTEXT\r\n- Project: AstroBio-Gen astrobiology prediction platform for exoplanet analysis and biosignature detection, with JWST relevance.\r\n- Inputs:\r\n 1) Full codebase: /mnt/data/astrobio_gen-main (3).zip unzip and use as the single source of truth.\r\n 2) Architectural intent & target state: (use the accompanying description I provided in this chat as supplemental context).\r\n- Target runtime: RunPod GPU instances.\r\n- Objective: perform a final, deep-down analysis + comprehensive code fixes, then harden the system for distributed deep learning training and inference on RunPod.\r\n\r\nTOP-LEVEL OBJECTIVES (DO ALL)\r\n1) Attention Mechanisms (deep dive and fixes)\r\n - Enumerate all attention implementations/usages (Transformers, cross-attn, multi-head, Performer/Flash/Scaled Dot-Product, rotary rope, ALiBi, KV-cache, causal masks).\r\n - Verify math correctness: scaling factors, mask shapes/dtypes, logits stabilization, numerically safe softmax, precision (fp16/bf16), gradient stability, sequence-length handling, padding and attention biasing.\r\n - Audit support for FlashAttention / SDPA; gate by CUDA/torch versions; remove dead code; unify paths; benchmark both paths; default to the fastest safe kernel.\r\n - Validate causal/inference paths: KV-cache shapes, caching updates, no graph breaks with torch.compile; ensure variable-length batching correctness.\r\n - Fix any import/name/method errors; standardize interfaces; add unit tests with randomized shapes and extreme lengths.\r\n\r\n2) Rust Data Pipelines (ingest preprocess training dataloader)\r\n - Identify all Rust crates/bindings (e.g., pyo3, polars, arrow, parquet, datafusion, tokio). If Rust is missing but planned, scaffold a production-ready Rust ingestion layer as a Cargo workspace:\r\n - Crates: core-ingest (IO & schema), transform (feature engineering), bridge (pyo3 Python bindings), cli (ops tools).\r\n - Implement async IO, schema validation, columnar formats (Arrow/Parquet), deterministic shuffling, caching, and backpressure.\r\n - Provide Python wheels via maturin/pyo3 for seamless use in PyTorch DataPipes.\r\n - Add strict typing, error handling (thiserror/anyhow), logging (tracing), metrics (prometheus).\r\n - Run clippy (deny warnings), rustfmt, and unit/integration tests. No placeholders.\r\n\r\n3) Data Acquisition & Usage in Training\r\n - Map every dataset path, schema, transform, split, and sampler. Remove duplication. Enforce a single authoritative configuration.\r\n - Validate all downloaders (retry, checksum), schema enforcement, and type safety. Fail-fast on missing columns or units.\r\n - Ensure training uses only curated, versioned datasets; add small synthetic fixtures for CI smoke tests.\r\n - Implement deterministic data splits; document seeds; verify DataLoader worker_init_fn correctness and pinned memory for GPU.\r\n - Add DataPipes or IterableDatasets with backpressure and prefetch; ensure no CPU/GPU starvation on RunPod.\r\n\r\n4) Algorithmic Content & Accuracy\r\n - Catalog every model/algorithm (supervised, self-supervised, graph, climate surrogate U-Net/Transformer, spectral AE, fusion, etc.).\r\n - Verify losses, metrics, schedulers, mixed precision, gradient clipping, and EMA. Remove unused hyperparams.\r\n - Add end-to-end correctness tests on tiny batches; calibrate metrics; add quick-reference baselines and ablations.\r\n - Implement sanity checks for physical constraints (where applicable) as explicit assertions in training/eval loops.\r\n\r\n5) LLM Setup & Readiness\r\n - Audit tokenizer/model alignment, EOS/BOS handling, padding side, RoPE scaling if long-context, safe generation defaults.\r\n - Ensure PEFT/LoRA/QLoRA paths compile with pinned versions; add tests for trainable param counts and state_dict merges.\r\n - Provide inference server (FastAPI/uvicorn) with streaming, batching, and GPU-aware memory guards; add JSON schemas.\r\n - Verify reproducible fine-tuning scripts on RunPod (DeepSpeed/FSDP if present); torch.compile compatibility; no fallbacks left half-implemented.\r\n\r\n6) Multimodal Structure Check\r\n - Trace all encoders/decoders/fusion blocks (tabular, graphs, climate cubes, spectra, text). Validate tensor shapes, masking conventions, time/lat/lon indexing, and dtype flow.\r\n - Standardize feature registries and modality contracts. Remove adapter dead-ends. Add cross-modal tests with dummy tensors.\r\n - Ensure exportable artifacts (TorchScript/ONNX) where feasible; document minimal inference graph per modality.\r\n\r\n7) Model Inventory & Competitiveness Review\r\n - Auto-discover all models by static analysis (Python/Rust/CLI). Build an inventory table: path, purpose, input/output shapes, params, training status, tests, last update.\r\n - Benchmark against strong baselines (clearly state chosen baselines). Report throughput, latency, memory, accuracy/metrics.\r\n - Recommend targeted upgrades (e.g., FlashAttention2, Triton kernels, better schedulers, improved augmentations) and implement immediately if scoped.\r\n\r\n8) Absolute Robustness & Hygiene\r\n - Eliminate ALL: import/name/method errors, shape/dtype mismatches, missing configs, silent catches, placeholder functions, TODOs.\r\n - Freeze dependency versions; add environment.yml + requirements.txt + optional Dockerfile.lock notes.\r\n - Pre-commit hooks: ruff/flake8, black, isort, mypy (strict for infra), pytest; clippy/rustfmt for Rust.\r\n - CI (GitHub Actions): build, lint, test (unit + smoke e2e), artifact upload.\r\n\r\n9) RunPod Readiness\r\n - Provide a CUDA 12.xcompatible Dockerfile: base (nvidia/cuda), Python pinned (PyTorch + CUDA toolkit), FlashAttention optional, system deps (git, build-essential, libaio), rustup if Rust is included.\r\n - Entry points: train.sh, evaluate.sh, infer_api.sh; parameterize via env vars; mount volumes for datasets/checkpoints.\r\n - Add a RunPod README with instance selection, image build/pull, volume mounts, and single-command launch lines.\r\n\r\nMANDATORY CONSTRAINTS\r\n- No module/import/name/method errors. No placeholders. No partial stubs. No TODO.\r\n- Prefer production-grade fixes over adding guards/fallbacks that mask problems.\r\n- Keep all key paths torch.compile-friendly. Respect AMP (bf16/fp16) and autocast scopes.\r\n- Deterministic training option available via flags (seed all RNGs), with a documented performance impact.\r\n\r\nDELIVERABLES (WRITE THEM INTO THE REPO)\r\n1) /HARDENING_REPORT.md\r\n - Executive summary of issues found and resolved.\r\n - Model inventory table (as above).\r\n - Attention audit results & benchmarks.\r\n - Data pipeline/Rust architecture diagram and rationale.\r\n - Multimodal contract diagrams (per modality).\r\n - Competitiveness analysis vs baselines; concrete next-win items.\r\n\r\n2) /RUNPOD_README.md\r\n - Exact commands to build/pull image and launch training/eval/inference.\r\n - Hardware matrix (A100/4090/H100) with recommended flags.\r\n - Troubleshooting section for common GPU/cuda/driver pitfalls.\r\n\r\n3) Working CI: .github/workflows/{python.yml,rust.yml}\r\n4) Dockerfile (+ optional docker-compose.yaml)\r\n5) Tests:\r\n - pytest unit & integration (seeded, <2 min smoke end-to-end: ingest dataloader 1 train step eval).\r\n - Rust cargo test suite with data contract tests.\r\n6) Scripts: train.sh, eval.sh, infer_api.sh (executable, documented).\r\n7) Version-pinned env files: environment.yml, requirements.txt, pyproject.toml (if used); Cargo.lock for Rust.\r\n\r\nVERIFICATION / ACCEPTANCE CRITERIA (AUTOMATE THESE)\r\n- `python -m pip install -e .` succeeds in fresh container.\r\n- `pytest -q` passes all tests.\r\n- `cargo test` passes with `-D warnings`.\r\n- `python train.py --quick-smoke` runs 1 epoch (or 10 steps) end-to-end on synthetic data without OOM or graph breaks.\r\n- `python serve.py` (or FastAPI entry) starts and answers a sample request with valid JSON.\r\n- `torch.cuda.is_available()` true; flash/sdpa path chosen based on capability; attention tests pass for seq_lens {16, 256, 4096}.\r\n- Data ingest CLI completes sample fetch + schema validation; produces a parquet/arrow shard; Python bridge loads it.\r\n\r\nWORK PLAN (YOU EXECUTE NOW, STEP BY STEP)\r\nA) Bootstrap\r\n - Unzip repo; index files; build dependency graph; detect Python/Rust/CI/Docker assets; resolve env; list all failing imports.\r\nB) Static Code Analysis\r\n - Trace attention code paths, models, dataloaders; list all error sites; propose fix set; apply & retest iteratively.\r\nC) Rust Pipeline\r\n - If present: harden; else: implement as specified; integrate with Python; add tests.\r\nD) Multimodal & LLM\r\n - Validate shapes/contracts; repair fusion; ensure tokenizer-model parity; fix PEFT paths; add tests.\r\nE) Benchmarks & Competitiveness\r\n - Implement micro/macro benchmarks; record in HARDENING_REPORT.md; optimize low-hanging fruit.\r\nF) RunPod Containerization\r\n - Build image; run smoke tests; finalize docs.\r\nG) CI & Final Sweep\r\n - Wire up Actions; ensure green builds; remove dead code; finalize docs.\r\n\r\nREPORTING\r\n- Keep a running changelog in HARDENING_REPORT.md with commit hashes and rationale.\r\n- If you must make an assumption, encode it as an explicit, tested contract and document it.\r\n\r\nBEGIN NOW.\r\n","rich_text_json_repr":{"type":"doc","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"SYSTEM / ROLE\r"},{"type":"hardBreak"},{"type":"text","text":"You are Augment Code, acting as a principal ML/Systems engineer and code auditor.
